    "summary": "The Roman Conquest of Greece (146 BC) is conventionally dated to the Roman sack of Corinth in 146 BC following the [[event:1065|Macedonian Wars]], though Rome had been exerting increasing control over Greek affairs for decades. The sack of Corinth, one of antiquity's richest cities, and the simultaneous [[event:1059|Destruction of Carthage]] in the same year marked Rome's emergence as the uncontested master of the Mediterranean world.\n\nRome had been involved in Greek affairs since the late third century BC, initially presenting itself as a liberator from Macedonian domination. After defeating Philip V at [[event:1066|Battle of Cynoscephalae]] and Antiochus III at [[event:1156|Battle of Magnesia]], Rome grew impatient with Greek political instability and anti-Roman sentiment in the [[event:1203|Achaean League]]. When Corinth defied Roman authority, the consul Lucius Mummius sacked and burned the city in 146 BC, killing or enslaving its population and shipping its art treasures to Rome. Greece became the Roman province of Macedonia, with the southern regions organized separately as Achaea.\n\nThe cultural significance of Greece's conquest was paradoxical. The Roman poet Horace later wrote 'Graecia capta ferum victorem cepit' — 'Captive Greece conquered its fierce captor' — referring to how thoroughly Greek culture, philosophy, and art penetrated Roman civilization. Elite Romans learned Greek, read Greek philosophy, collected Greek art, and employed Greek tutors for their children. The Hellenistic cultural synthesis that [[event:75|Alexander the Great's Empire]] had spread across the Near East was now transmitted into Latin civilization through this Roman absorption of Greece.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Corinth_(146_BC)",
